---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Learn about aurora borealis — what causes the northern lights, how to see them, and how space weather is monitored."
>
  <!-- Page Hero -->
  <div class="about-hero">
    <h1 class="hero-title">WHAT IS THE AURORA?</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">
      The aurora borealis — or northern lights — is one of Earth's most spectacular natural phenomena.
      Caused by charged particles from the Sun interacting with Earth's magnetosphere, auroras paint
      the night sky in ribbons of green, purple, magenta, and white.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Science Section -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">How Auroras Form</h2>
    <div class="science-grid">
      <div class="science-step card">
        <div class="step-number">01</div>
        <div class="step-icon">☀️</div>
        <h3 class="step-title">Solar Wind</h3>
        <p class="step-desc">
          The Sun constantly emits a stream of charged particles — mostly electrons and protons —
          called the solar wind. During solar flares and coronal mass ejections (CMEs), this
          outflow intensifies dramatically, sending billions of tons of magnetized plasma toward Earth.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="science-step card">
        <div class="step-number">02</div>
        <div class="step-icon">🌍</div>
        <h3 class="step-title">Magnetosphere Interaction</h3>
        <p class="step-desc">
          Earth's magnetic field deflects most solar wind. However, when the interplanetary magnetic
          field tilts southward (negative Bz), it can connect with Earth's field and allow particles
          to funnel down toward the polar regions along magnetic field lines.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="science-step card">
        <div class="step-number">03</div>
        <div class="step-icon">💫</div>
        <h3 class="step-title">Atmospheric Collision</h3>
        <p class="step-desc">
          Energetic particles collide with atmospheric gases at altitudes between 100–300 km.
          Oxygen atoms emit green light at ~120 km and red at higher altitudes. Nitrogen molecules
          produce blue and purple hues. The result: nature's most breathtaking light show.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="science-step card">
        <div class="step-number">04</div>
        <div class="step-icon">🌐</div>
        <h3 class="step-title">Auroral Oval</h3>
        <p class="step-desc">
          Aurora activity concentrates in a ring-shaped region around the geomagnetic poles called
          the auroral oval. During quiet conditions this sits around 65–70°N. During strong storms
          (Kp 7–9) it can expand to 40°N — making auroras visible across much of Europe and North America.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Space Weather Scales -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">NOAA Space Weather Scales</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      NOAA uses three scales to communicate the severity of space weather events to the public,
      emergency services, and critical infrastructure operators.
    </p>

    <div class="scales-grid">
      <!-- Geomagnetic -->
      <div class="scale-card card">
        <div class="scale-header">
          <span class="scale-big-letter">G</span>
          <div>
            <div class="scale-title">Geomagnetic Storms</div>
            <div class="scale-subtitle">Driven by Kp Index</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="scale-levels">
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge g1">G1</span>
            <span class="level-kp">Kp 5</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Minor — Aurora at 60°N+. Power grid fluctuations possible.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge g2">G2</span>
            <span class="level-kp">Kp 6</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Moderate — Aurora at 55°N. High-latitude power systems affected.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge g3">G3</span>
            <span class="level-kp">Kp 7</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Strong — Aurora at 50°N. Widespread voltage problems. GPS errors.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge g4">G4</span>
            <span class="level-kp">Kp 8</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Severe — Aurora at 45°N. Power outages. Satellite issues.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge g5">G5</span>
            <span class="level-kp">Kp 9</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Extreme — Aurora at 40°N. Widespread power outages. Carrington-class.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Solar Radiation -->
      <div class="scale-card card">
        <div class="scale-header">
          <span class="scale-big-letter">S</span>
          <div>
            <div class="scale-title">Solar Radiation Storms</div>
            <div class="scale-subtitle">Driven by Proton Flux (≥10 MeV)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="scale-levels">
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge s1">S1</span>
            <span class="level-kp">10 pfu</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Minor — Weak HF radio blackouts on sunlit side.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge s2">S2</span>
            <span class="level-kp">100 pfu</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Moderate — Infrequent single-event upsets in satellites.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge s3">S3</span>
            <span class="level-kp">1,000 pfu</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Strong — Radiation hazard to astronauts. Memory device errors.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge s4">S4</span>
            <span class="level-kp">10,000 pfu</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Severe — Star-tracker issues. HF radio blackout on entire sunlit side.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge s5">S5</span>
            <span class="level-kp">100,000 pfu</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Extreme — Complete HF blackout. Severe radiation to astronauts.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Radio Blackouts -->
      <div class="scale-card card">
        <div class="scale-header">
          <span class="scale-big-letter">R</span>
          <div>
            <div class="scale-title">Radio Blackouts</div>
            <div class="scale-subtitle">Driven by X-ray Flux</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="scale-levels">
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge r1">R1</span>
            <span class="level-kp">M1</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Minor — Weak or minor degradation of HF radio. Occasional loss.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge r2">R2</span>
            <span class="level-kp">M5</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Moderate — Limited blackout of HF radio 10–15 min. Low-frequency navigation errors.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge r3">R3</span>
            <span class="level-kp">X1</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Strong — Wide area blackout of HF radio, 1 hour. Low-frequency navigation out.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge r4">R4</span>
            <span class="level-kp">X10</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Severe — HF radio blackout on most of sunlit side for 1–2 hours.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="level-row">
            <span class="level-badge r5">R5</span>
            <span class="level-kp">X20</span>
            <span class="level-desc">Extreme — Complete HF blackout on entire sunlit side for hours.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Best Places Section -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Best Places to See Auroras</h2>
    <div class="places-grid">
      <div class="place-card card">
        <div class="place-flag">🇳🇴</div>
        <h3 class="place-name">Tromsø, Norway</h3>
        <div class="place-lat">69.6°N</div>
        <p class="place-desc">Inside the auroral oval for most of the year. Dark polar nights from Nov–Feb. World-class infrastructure for aurora tourism.</p>
        <div class="place-tags">
          <span class="badge badge-green">BEST VIEWING</span>
          <span class="badge badge-cyan">OCT–MAR</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="place-card card">
        <div class="place-flag">🇮🇸</div>
        <h3 class="place-name">Iceland</h3>
        <div class="place-lat">64–66°N</div>
        <p class="place-desc">Vast dark landscapes, minimal light pollution, and a Kp 3+ is enough for visibility. Reykjavik still has good dark sky access nearby.</p>
        <div class="place-tags">
          <span class="badge badge-green">HIGHLY RECOMMENDED</span>
          <span class="badge badge-cyan">SEP–APR</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="place-card card">
        <div class="place-flag">🇫🇮</div>
        <h3 class="place-name">Finnish Lapland</h3>
        <div class="place-lat">68–70°N</div>
        <p class="place-desc">Average of 200 aurora nights per year in Saariselkä. Glass-roofed cabins offer lying-in-bed viewing. Magical winter landscape.</p>
        <div class="place-tags">
          <span class="badge badge-green">HIGHLY RECOMMENDED</span>
          <span class="badge badge-cyan">NOV–MAR</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="place-card card">
        <div class="place-flag">🇺🇸</div>
        <h3 class="place-name">Fairbanks, Alaska</h3>
        <div class="place-lat">64.8°N</div>
        <p class="place-desc">Home to Poker Flat Research Range, the world's largest land-based rocket research facility. Clear, cold nights make for excellent aurora viewing.</p>
        <div class="place-tags">
          <span class="badge badge-yellow">GOOD OPTION</span>
          <span class="badge badge-cyan">OCT–MAR</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="place-card card">
        <div class="place-flag">🇨🇦</div>
        <h3 class="place-name">Yukon, Canada</h3>
        <div class="place-lat">60–65°N</div>
        <p class="place-desc">Whitehorse sits directly under the auroral oval. Extremely clear skies and low humidity make for sharp, vivid displays from Sept–April.</p>
        <div class="place-tags">
          <span class="badge badge-green">HIGHLY RECOMMENDED</span>
          <span class="badge badge-cyan">AUG–APR</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="place-card card">
        <div class="place-flag">🇳🇿</div>
        <h3 class="place-name">New Zealand (South)</h3>
        <div class="place-lat">44–46°S</div>
        <p class="place-desc">Aurora Australis (southern lights) visible from Otago and Fiordland, especially during strong storms. Kp 5+ usually needed.</p>
        <div class="place-tags">
          <span class="badge badge-purple">AURORA AUSTRALIS</span>
          <span class="badge badge-cyan">MAR–SEP</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Photography Section -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Aurora Photography Guide</h2>
    <div class="photo-guide card">
      <div class="photo-cols">
        <div class="photo-col">
          <h3 class="photo-col-title">Camera Settings</h3>
          <div class="settings-list">
            <div class="setting-row">
              <span class="setting-name">ISO</span>
              <span class="setting-val">800 – 3200</span>
              <span class="setting-note">Start at 1600, adjust for conditions</span>
            </div>
            <div class="setting-row">
              <span class="setting-name">Aperture</span>
              <span class="setting-val">f/1.8 – f/2.8</span>
              <span class="setting-note">As wide as your lens allows</span>
            </div>
            <div class="setting-row">
              <span class="setting-name">Shutter</span>
              <span class="setting-val">5 – 25 sec</span>
              <span class="setting-note">Faster for active aurora to avoid blur</span>
            </div>
            <div class="setting-row">
              <span class="setting-name">Focus</span>
              <span class="setting-val">Manual ∞</span>
              <span class="setting-note">Auto-focus will struggle in the dark</span>
            </div>
            <div class="setting-row">
              <span class="setting-name">White Balance</span>
              <span class="setting-val">3500 – 4500K</span>
              <span class="setting-note">Or shoot RAW and adjust later</span>
            </div>
            <div class="setting-row">
              <span class="setting-name">Format</span>
              <span class="setting-val">RAW</span>
              <span class="setting-note">Essential for post-processing flexibility</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="photo-col">
          <h3 class="photo-col-title">Gear Checklist</h3>
          <ul class="gear-list">
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Wide-angle lens (14–24mm recommended)</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Sturdy tripod — essential in the cold</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Extra batteries (cold drains them fast)</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Remote shutter release or timer</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Head torch with red mode</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Lens cloth (watch for condensation)</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Hand warmers — for you and the battery</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">✓</span> Aurora forecast app (Space Weather by NOAA)</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="photo-col-title" style="margin-top: 24px;">Composing Your Shot</h3>
          <ul class="gear-list">
            <li><span class="gear-check">→</span> Include a dark foreground for scale</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">→</span> Trees, mountains, or water reflections add drama</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">→</span> Point slightly north — that's where the action is</li>
            <li><span class="gear-check">→</span> Milky Way can coexist with mild aurora nights</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Resources Section -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Monitoring Resources</h2>
    <div class="resources-grid">
      <a href="https://www.swpc.noaa.gov/communities/aurora-dashboard-experimental" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="resource-card card">
        <div class="resource-logo">NOAA</div>
        <div class="resource-info">
          <h3 class="resource-title">NOAA Aurora Dashboard</h3>
          <p class="resource-desc">Official US government space weather forecasting. Real-time Kp index, aurora oval maps, solar wind data, and 3-day outlooks.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://www.spaceweather.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="resource-card card">
        <div class="resource-logo">SW</div>
        <div class="resource-info">
          <h3 class="resource-title">SpaceWeather.com</h3>
          <p class="resource-desc">Daily space weather news, solar images, and aurora alert subscriptions. Great for learning about current solar activity.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://www.gi.alaska.edu/monitors/aurora-forecast" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="resource-card card">
        <div class="resource-logo">UAF</div>
        <div class="resource-info">
          <h3 class="resource-title">UAF Aurora Forecast</h3>
          <p class="resource-desc">University of Alaska Fairbanks Geophysical Institute. Regional aurora forecasts and all-sky camera feeds from Alaska.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://services.swpc.noaa.gov/images/animations/ovation/north/latest.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="resource-card card">
        <div class="resource-logo">OVT</div>
        <div class="resource-info">
          <h3 class="resource-title">OVATION Aurora Model</h3>
          <p class="resource-desc">NOAA's real-time aurora oval forecast model. 30-minute probabilistic prediction of aurora intensity and location globally.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://kp.gfz-potsdam.de/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="resource-card card">
        <div class="resource-logo">GFZ</div>
        <div class="resource-info">
          <h3 class="resource-title">GFZ Kp Index</h3>
          <p class="resource-desc">Official Kp index data from the German Research Centre for Geosciences. Historical data, real-time values, and forecasts.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://aurorasaurus.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="resource-card card">
        <div class="resource-logo">A★</div>
        <div class="resource-info">
          <h3 class="resource-title">Aurorasaurus</h3>
          <p class="resource-desc">Citizen science platform for real-time aurora sightings. Community reports help map actual visibility beyond model predictions.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="resource-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-grid">
      <div class="faq-item card">
        <h3 class="faq-q">What Kp level do I need to see the aurora?</h3>
        <p class="faq-a">It depends on your latitude. At 65°N (Iceland, Tromsø), Kp 3 is enough. At 55°N (Scotland, southern Norway), you need Kp 5+. In central Europe or the northern US, you typically need Kp 7 or higher. During the extreme G5 storm of May 2024, aurora was visible as far south as Florida and Texas.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item card">
        <h3 class="faq-q">Why does Bz southward enhance aurora activity?</h3>
        <p class="faq-a">When the interplanetary magnetic field (IMF) Bz component points south, it can "reconnect" with Earth's northward-pointing magnetic field in a process called magnetic reconnection. This opens a window allowing solar wind particles to enter the magnetosphere and flow toward the poles, dramatically increasing aurora activity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item card">
        <h3 class="faq-q">What causes different aurora colors?</h3>
        <p class="faq-a">Colors depend on which gas is excited and at what altitude. Oxygen at ~100 km produces the most common green. Oxygen at higher altitudes (200–300 km) creates red. Nitrogen molecules at low altitudes emit blue and purple. The rare all-red "SAR arc" appears during very strong storms.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item card">
        <h3 class="faq-q">Are we near solar maximum?</h3>
        <p class="faq-a">Solar Cycle 25 is currently near or past its peak. NOAA predicted the maximum around mid-2025, meaning 2024–2026 represents some of the best aurora viewing conditions in over a decade. The historic G5 storm of May 2024 demonstrated this dramatically with global aurora visibility.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item card">
        <h3 class="faq-q">How far in advance can aurora be forecast?</h3>
        <p class="faq-a">Reliable forecasting is limited to about 1–3 days. When a CME is detected leaving the Sun, scientists can predict when it'll reach Earth within a few hours. Once the solar wind reaches the DSCOVR satellite at L1 (about 1.5M km from Earth), there's 15–60 minutes of advance warning.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item card">
        <h3 class="faq-q">Can I see aurora with the naked eye?</h3>
        <p class="faq-a">Yes! During moderate to strong events (Kp 5+), aurora is clearly visible with the naked eye from mid-to-high latitudes. Cameras — even phone cameras — often detect fainter displays that eyes miss, since sensors are more sensitive to green wavelengths in low light. Never dismiss a faint glow without taking a photo first.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* ─── Hero ─── */
  .about-hero {
    margin-bottom: 56px;
    max-width: 820px;
  }

  .hero-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(36px, 6vw, 72px);
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: var(--text-white);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    text-shadow:
      0 0 40px rgba(57, 255, 138, 0.4),
      0 0 80px rgba(168, 85, 247, 0.2);
  }

  .hero-sub {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    max-width: 700px;
  }

  /* ─── Content sections ─── */
  .content-section {
    margin-bottom: 64px;
  }

  .section-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(20px, 3vw, 30px);
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-white);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 10px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  }

  .section-intro {
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    max-width: 700px;
  }

  /* ─── Science steps ─── */
  .science-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 16px;
  }

  .science-step {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 12px;
    position: relative;
  }

  .step-number {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 48px;
    color: rgba(255,255,255,0.06);
    line-height: 1;
    position: absolute;
    top: 12px;
    right: 16px;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
  }

  .step-icon { font-size: 28px; }

  .step-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 20px;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: var(--text-white);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .step-desc {
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* ─── Scales grid ─── */
  .scales-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 20px;
  }

  .scale-card { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 20px; }

  .scale-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 16px;
    padding-bottom: 16px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);
  }

  .scale-big-letter {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 64px;
    line-height: 1;
    color: var(--text-white);
    text-shadow: 0 0 30px rgba(255,255,255,0.3);
  }

  .scale-title    { font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-white); }
  .scale-subtitle { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 2px; }

  .scale-levels { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }

  .level-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 36px 60px 1fr;
    gap: 8px;
    align-items: start;
    font-size: 12px;
  }

  .level-badge {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 2px;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .level-kp  { color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 11px; align-self: center; }
  .level-desc { color: var(--text-dim); line-height: 1.5; }

  /* G scale colors */
  .g1 { background: rgba(57,255,138,0.2); color: #39ff8a; }
  .g2 { background: rgba(162,255,57,0.2); color: #a2ff39; }
  .g3 { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.2); color: #fbbf24; }
  .g4 { background: rgba(249,115,22,0.2); color: #f97316; }
  .g5 { background: rgba(248,113,113,0.2); color: #f87171; }

  /* S scale colors */
  .s1 { background: rgba(34,211,238,0.2); color: #22d3ee; }
